⛪ MATTHEW 10:28 / church
crow 🕊 jacob de silva 18-Nov-21 09:06 AM
@congregation It’s a beautiful day in Meteor City. The weather is a bit chilly today, but you’re walking the streets for some reason — maybe you’re looking for something, or visiting a friend, or going to your favorite laundromat. Attending a church luncheon. Whatever the case, you seem to find it — a stone settles deep in your gut, though you’re not sure why. It’s the feeling of wrongness that pervades just by being in Meteor City, where things are tilted just one degree more than usual. Then you realize it — there is a street here when there wasn't before. There shouldn't be, but it’s here now… It’s obvious to the city natives and the long-time residents, though no one on the street barely blinks an eye. Many things appear in Meteor City; a street is just one of them. The road is blocked off ahead from cars; foot traffic only, the sign says. No cars allowed.

SYLVESTER BOT 18-Nov-21 09:29 AM
It was not a matter of if Sylvester notices the street appearing, it was a matter of when. Cursory surveillance did not prove enough when investigations turned out very little information on the location of their two missing colleagues. Of course despite their best efforts, it appeared when no one was looking— Or perhaps it was always there, but simply did not allow for them to see. The streets were like that sometimes, with a life of their own they followed the whims of the city. The sunny weather didn’t feel appropriate. Sylvester found himself approaching the location, bag slung across his shoulder. Albert and Parker were already there— So Sylvester found himself glancing around, mismatched eyes settling on the sign. Foot traffic only. It really was like an event, he thought. An anniversary, an ending. A last sermon. Sylvester smiles, although it held very little mirth. He hasn’t properly gone to church in two decades. The last time was— The angel case. A blood bath. Judgement, struck down by something that pretended to be holy. He hoped it wouldn’t end the same way. “I assume you are all attending too?” He finally asks, looking at his colleagues. @hyulidays 👓 albert 🕶 sang-hoon @li | ernest 🐶🛌 parker

Though he didn't think he could offer much, and he most certainly didn't want to go back, it didn't sit right with him to just leave Albert to his own devices—his own lonely devices again. Adrian Liu BOT 18-Nov-21 09:45 AM
"..." They're stopped at a light. Ernest is even more distant than usual, all distracted answers and absentminded fidgeting. It probably has something to do with Jacob—Adrian's lips purse subtly, gloved fingers tapping out a syncopated rhythm against the steering wheel. It's not that he doesn't care about whatever's been going on, but the office had its fair share of employees going "missing" every week. Half the time it was some impromptu hiatus, spurred on by a particularly challenging mission. He's sure the good Reverend's seen challenging things, on his missions. Maybe he's even been the cause of them. Adrian represses a grimace. If Jacob was lost in Pleasantville again, Adrian doesn't see how it's his problem. Ernest's soft request breaks him out of his dark thoughts. Adrian glances out the passenger-side window, noticing the sealed-off street. He doesn't give it much thought, until he notices a few familiar-looking detectives lurking around what he assumes to be a roadwork notice, and... Ah. His eye catches on something in the curb, something not-quite-right about the street in question. "You don't think..." He sighs, batting his turn signal on as he complies, doing another circle around the block. In a minute or two, they're back, his car stopped just before the sealed-off intersection, as if to turn right. Some of his coworkers seem to have already noticed. Just their luck. He stares down the length of the mysterious street. It seems harmless enough. A strange feeling twists in his gut. The joints of his fingers ache. He flexes and unflexes his hand, his expression clouded as he shoots Ernest a knowing glance. "...I don't like this." @li | ernest 🐶🛌 parker

crow 🕊 jacob de silva 18-Nov-21 10:08 AM
@congregation
GENESIS 1:1-2 ;In the beginning God created the heavens and the earth. Now the earth was formless and empty, darkness was over the surface of the deep, and the Spirit of God was hovering over the waters.
It’s a beautiful, god-blessed day at St. Lucia. You check your watch, or your phone. The face reads [9:00AM,] bright and early. It’s such a nice day out, too — despite the fall weather, the sun is already high in the sky, shedding gentle warmth down upon you all. It’s such a warm, calming feeling, one you might associate with the advent of spring. It’s hard to forget that in just a few weeks, the streets will be caked with ice and snow, glittering down upon you all. For now, it’s just you and the church. For those of you unfamiliar with it, it’s not as modest as a name ‘chapel’ would suggest. It’s a full on cathedral, though lacks the ornamentation and detailing of what a cathedral might’ve looked like in your head. After all, those cathedrals were hundreds of years old, foundations of human history. And, well, St. Lucia might still be able to become a foundation — but really, it’s only 10 years old, freshly turned. Today is the inauguration of its 10th anniversary, with the flyers posted on the front gates and scattered upon the lawn proudly declaring the fact. Its stones are washed white, though turned grey after having been through all types of weather in Meteor City. The doors are propped open, and you can see a long corridor within, ending at the very back with an altar and stained glass. It’s impressive — and welcoming. Once you step into the shade of its arches, the coolness lifts the heat from your skin and envelops you in a quiet, reverent silence; you are trespassing in the Lord’s holy space, now. The doors are open, even to sinners like you. There are some people in the pews. All sorts of people, who have come to pray and adore. There’s no sign of someone waiting to brief you, or greet you. Did you get the day right? Just another Thursday, you suppose.

GENESIS 1:3 ;And God said, “Let there be light,” and there was light.
Jacob’s words echo across the open space of the church as he says those words, standing at the head of the altar. He projects a different kind of energy than what you usually saw; here, he is the leader, the sheep of his flock. The light rings around his head like a halo, illuminates him against the backdrop of the setting sun. He catches your eye and smiles. “The word of the Lord,” he says, and the murmur that passes through the church is hard to resist. Those who know what to say find themselves saying it; those who don’t still bow their heads. A spirit descends upon you all today, like a white-tongued flame, like a blessing. And when everyone goes to sit down, something comes through the closed doors of the courtyard. Jacob’s silent at the altar. When you look upon him, he looks perplexed, not making sense of the things he's seen. The candles flicker, then go out in a gust of wind, and then lights go out. Someone screams — but it’s only for a moment. It cuts out. You think you hear the sound of a heavy body falling to the floor to the back. There is something that moves through the crowd, through you — like a ghost, it infiltrates your thoughts, digs into it, buries a purpose. You’re filled with an overwhelming urge to protect, to keep safe, to preserve, to… Maybe some of you fight. And fight admirably. But as soon as it touches you, you’ll know that there is no way you can fight it. If you try to escape, the doors are locked. For the mass, of course. Then you’re ripped apart. Viciously. You can’t tell where the pain ends and when the numbness begins. You don’t experience a flash of memory, of a life well-lived, but you know, well and truly, that you’re dying. And you will be dead in a few moments. And then… what? What are your last thoughts, then, in a world without light? The evening always comes before the morning. You’ll be whole when the day comes. But at night, this is world without end.
GENESIS 1:4-5 ;God saw that the light was good, and he separated the light from the darkness. God called the light “day,” and the darkness he called “night.” And there was evening, and there was morning—the first day. [Amen.]
@congregation

GENESIS 1:6 ;And God said, “Let there be a vault between the waters to separate water from water.”
It’s a beautiful, god-blessed day at St. Lucia. You check your watch, or your phone. The face reads [9:00AM,] bright and early. You already knew that, though. It’s such a nice day out, too — despite the fall weather, the sun is already high in the sky, shedding gentle warmth down upon you all. It’s such a warm, calming feeling, one you might associate with the advent of spring. It’s hard to forget that in just a few weeks, the streets will be caked with ice and snow, glittering down upon you all. For now, it’s just you and the church. It’s intimidating — and quiet. Once you step into the shade of its arches, the coolness lifts the heat from your skin and envelops you in a quiet, reverent silence; you are trespassing in the Lord’s holy space, now. There are some people in the pews. All sorts of people, who have come to pray and adore. There’s no sign of someone waiting to brief you, or greet you. You knew that already, too. … Your body aches. You crack your neck, flex your hands, try to dispel the feeling. You got the day right. So… ?

Eunji Lim BOT 18-Nov-21 12:37 PM
Jacob belongs up there, haloed in the light. She can't help but think it a fitting scene, one of beauty, grace, artistry— and she's never put her faith in gods, higher beings, divinity... Why, with all these nerves wracking her system, it could beat right out of her chest! Something punches through her gut. It displaces her spine, she thinks. Her heart tumbles onto the floor, beating still. Badum, badum. Badum. Badum... Badum. Ba— She's not sure when she fell forward, knees buckling beneath the weight of— nothing. No more burdens to bear, for what was a heart but the sickening weight of connection? Tethering her to the world? To the living? To... to Feu? Who was that? No, she knows who Feu is. She knows who Eunji is. That's her. That's... that's. Her name. Her blood runs hot over her shirt, a crisp black blouse she'd donned for the occasion. Something bursts from her mouth, a spluttering of breath and viscera. Is that flesh that just crawled out of her throat? is it moving? No, her vision is hazy, it's a blur. It's getting darker. Her eyes strain to stay open. Eunji Lim lifts her gaze to the Reverend, to Luka. How beautiful. They remained silhouetted by the light, even now. She blinks, slow, dull. It's wet. Damp. She can feel her life leaving her, slow. Petering out, the steady drip of an IV. A dull laugh sounds from red lips, but the sound is so muddled, it rings in her ears as a bastardization of what it once was. She'd heard that, when you die, your hearing's the last to go. But all she hears is the tolling of a bell.
in the same will I die: and there will I be buried
For some reason, her vision is the last to go. Her eyes never shut. The flame dies. Then she's back. She goes to church.

Adrian Liu BOT 18-Nov-21 01:40 PM
The events, in as clean of an order as he can manage it. Clinical. Sanitized. 0. He fights. Of course he does. 1. Upon receiving a severe wound—particularly one inflicted by something passing through the body, a projectile, a blade, a bullet—skin, muscle, and bone shatter and cave around the foreign intruder. Even the skin outside and around the wound is stretched and lacerated. Ironically, this is the skin that registers the most pain. A sympathy ache, nerves still intact and firing at top speed. In the body’s many cavities, vital constructs are secured in place only by the tight embrace of flesh and skin. In its absence, muscle and organ and tissue fold in on themselves like a toppling tower of cards. 2. The body produces a flood of adrenaline to combat the perceived threat. To leap out of harm’s way. To override the pain and to keep running. The body doesn’t know, of course, that it’s already too late. The flood of adrenaline washes out the brain’s pain receptors as quickly as it sends the heart into a frantic overdrive. Ironically, a victim’s elevated pulse only serves to hasten the wound’s bleeding. In minutes, they lose enough blood for their vision to blur and fade to black, before they’ve even registered the pain. 3. In most near-death experiences, survivors report the following emotions, in varying orders. Panic. Desperation. Anger. Helplessness. Surrender. Acceptance. Numbness. Some even report peace, though Adrian has never been one to understand what that feels like. 4. In the darkness and in the last few moments of consciousness, it is impossible to see, the catastrophic dip in blood pressure diverting blood from the brain, the eyes, the body. Instead, he hears—
5. The quiet, reverent silence outside St. Lucia, where he now stands. The sun is warm on his face. There is no gaping hole where his heart should be. It is a beautiful day in Meteor City, and he is miraculously, disappointingly alive. His heart pumps blood through his body. One beat, then another, then twenty, and finally his legs obey him and he moves. One step. Another. His body obeys him, hesitantly. His jaw aches with how hard he’s clenching it, fingers curled into tight fists where they lie hidden in his coat pockets. His first explanation is a hallucination of anomalous origins. His second is irrelevant. His conclusion: if he had experienced it, whatever it was, the others must have as well. The others. He whirls around, getting his bearings. He notices a familiar silhouette, dialing a number with shaking hands. His jaw shudders open, like a rusty hinge. "Ernest," he calls. His voice is too flat, too unaffected, some remnant of shock still in his system. He tries again, regardless. "You're alright." He means for it to come out as a question; his voice disobeys, turning it into a quiet statement. The church bells are ringing. @li | ernest 🐶🛌 parker

crow 🕊 jacob de silva 18-Nov-21 05:01 PM
GENESIS 1:17-18 ;God set them in the vault of the sky to give light on the earth, to govern the day and the night, and to separate light from darkness. And God saw that it was good.
The cross unhinges and swings down. Then you realize why the shape was so different — its end is pointed, like a skewer. You can imagine how someone dies, at the end of that. Albert sees it while Jacob is still talking, and pushes him out of the way. But Luka sees it too, and Luka — she always prioritized others before herself, so of course she goes to save Jacob too, even without looking. The cross impales her. Presumably, her heart stops, and then you make the connection, all of you, as the world violently turns into black — The loop foundation is Luka. Moreso than that, the loop foundation is her death. And piecing it together, about protecting, about wanting to keep this mystery person safe... Well, death is not safe. And you want a redo. And you want to start it over. And aren't the safest creatures the ones under glass cages, going around and around in their tank, never leaving? That's what St. Lucia was to Luka. And you are all simply trapped in it. You don't die, but she does. And that means —
GENESIS 1:19 ;And there was evening, and there was morning—the fourth day.

He is a bright, sunny day! Albert stands, or tries to, his legs failing him as his head spins in every direction at once. Inevitably, he stumbles a bit before trying to catch himself and push his way to the entrance of the church. SYLVESTER BOT 20-Nov-21 09:36 AM
He took a breath and felt his mind unfold again. It was an arduous process, a checklist of senses awakening. Dried blood on skin, crumbling and flaking off like dust. A cold chill, a warmth from deep within, a scream echoing from the depths of an endless pit. Opening his eyes, it was dark but that was nothing new, it was familiar. The pain, not so much. He almost forgot, how much it stings, it screams in his head. How the ache becomes an entity in itself, an intruder in an otherwise working mind. It demands attention, something is wrong, why won’t you fix it, why does it not go away? He sat up, just to witness his colleagues entering with no hesitation. Adrian. Albert. Parker. He rolled the names around his head, feeling a satisfaction that he can recall things again. He lifts an arm— That’s the trapezius and the serratus anterior, the pectoralis moving in tandem to adjust a pair of glasses, smeared in blood. The world was red, and dark, and blurry, but he saw movement he saw people. “It’s nice to see you all again.” He says, to no one in particular, watching the backs of his colleagues enter hell again. The entrance of the church was broken, and devoid of life. He should join them. He does.

Adrian Liu BOT 20-Nov-21 11:37 AM
He takes a breath. He doesn’t feel anything, fear or guilt or anticipation, and he doesn’t need to wonder why that is. Did the man know? Of course he did. He raises the gun to the man’s head, then drops it to aim over his heart, both hands bracing the grip of the gun. Shoot the right place. There was only one way to be sure, after all. The logical solution. A modern pistol holds six to seven rounds, and a handgun over double that amount. A modern handgun can fire off its entire magazine in the span of seconds. He had to be sure. It was the logical solution. Logic. A shot to the head that passes through the brain stem stops the neurological governance of key unconscious processes: the regulation of breathing, the heartbeat, the signals in a body that keeps it on its feet. It was merciful. But a falling body was harder to hit. A breath. A beat. Then: Bang! A gunshot tears through the man’s chest. Adrian knows what it feels like. Blood splatters out behind him, across stone floors and wooden pews. Before he can stumble or stagger, Adrian raises the gun once more, and shoots him over and over again: through the eye, through the forehead, through the neck—the gut, the lungs, the limbs. Everywhere he can hit, even as the man staggers and falls. After a certain point, he stops aiming entirely. He only stops when the gun clicks hollowly, out of ammo. His ears ring from the deafening shots; he can’t hear a thing outside of his pulse roaring in his ears, rabbit-quick. There’s blood on his arms, his face. He feels as empty as the magazine under his hands. @mistledodo | luka

5
Parker Lestrade BOT 18-Nov-21 11:06 AM
So basically not Eden at all in the end, huh? Parker feels his shoes graze the pavement of the path, and he plaintively takes in the sight. Yes, it's completely empty. Yes, there was no point in being here. But was it a crime to be here? Was it a sin to be alone? Parker makes his way to the gazebo and sits down with a grunt, arms resting on his lap as he hunched over. His fingers lace together comfortably, and seeing he was already slightly unsettled by this uncanny return of his 'missing' coworkers, he figures he may as well just do what he usually does here. If not to serve some purpose, than just... for no reason. That's how he always prayed, anyway. For no reason. Because he felt like it might do something, someday. Somewhere. So he laces his hands, and not even going so far as to mutter the words, he merely recites them in his head with his eyes closed. ...in what I have done and in what I have failed to do, by my fault, by my fault, by my most grievous fault; wherefore I pray God Almighty to have mercy on me, forgive me all my sins, and bring me to everlasting life. Amen. It's not one of those ones you're supposed to recite in private, but whatever. It was the one that applied to him the most. He does a quick tap to his forehead and shoulders, a half-baked sign of the cross, and them briskly gets up to rejoin the congregation. @mistledodo | luka @crow 🕊 jacob de silva ▶️ #church
